AVIAN INFLUENZA - WORLDWIDE (09): NIGERIA
*****************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1]
Date: Sat, 11 Feb 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Reuters alertnet, 10 Feb 2006 [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L10280820.htm>

Genetic sequencing on the H5N1 avian flu virus from birds in Nigeria
show it is virtually the same as that found in fowl in China and
Turkey, a scientist said on Friday [10 Feb 2006].
A laboratory in Padua, Italy carried out the test on behalf of 2
international agencies dealing with the outbreaks in animals, the
U.N. Food and Agriculture Organisation (FAO) and World Organisation
for Animal Health (OIE).
The H5N1 virus was found in dead poultry in northern Nigeria, the 1st
time it has been detected in Africa after spreading across Asia and
along the Black Sea.
"It is virtually identical to the [virus affecting] birds in Qinghai
Lake, China and the chickens in Turkey," Ilaria Capua, who carried
out the genetic sequencing at the Padua laboratory, told Reuters.
"This is the full sequence of one sample," she added.
The World Health Organisation [WHO] has said that the viruses from
Turkey's first 2 fatal human cases were virtually identical to
viruses from Qinghai Lake nature reserve in central China, where
there was an unprecedented die-off of 6000 migratory birds in April 2005.
