[Those interested in programs addressing the epidemiology of avian
influenza in wild birds, particularly if related to Europe, may refer
to the following 4 presentations which were made by different experts
during the Standing Committee on the Food Chain and Animal Health
(SCFCAH) working group meeting on 6 Sep 2005 (ref 1 includes maps on
bird migration; refs 2 and 4 include collected virological data from
wild birds):
1) David Stroud, Wetlands International. NEW-FLUBIRD Network for
early warning of influenza viruses in migratory birds in Europe. Key
Activity 1: Ornithological studies and sampling activities.
<http://europa.eu.int/comm/food/animal/diseases/controlmeasures/avian/birds.pdf>.
2) Department of Virology, Erasmus MC, Rotterdam. Proposal for a EU
collaboration:
<http://europa.eu.int/comm/food/animal/diseases/controlmeasures/avian/early_warning.pdf>NEW-FLUBIRD
- Network for early warning of influenza viruses in migratory birds in Europe.
<http://europa.eu.int/comm/food/animal/diseases/controlmeasures/avian/early_warning.pdf>.
3) Bjorn Olsen, Ottenby Bird Observatory. European Collaboration on
AIV monitoring in wild birds.
<http://europa.eu.int/comm/food/animal/diseases/controlmeasures/avian/wild_birds.pdf>.
4) Ian Brown, Community Reference Laboratory, Veterinary Laboratories
Agency, UK. Surveys for avian influenza in poultry and wild birds in
member states 2004.
<http://europa.eu.int/comm/food/animal/diseases/controlmeasures/avian/eu_ai_survey2004_en.pdf>.
New studies into the epidemiology of H5N1, authored by 28
investigators from China (Guandong, Fujian), Hong-Kong, Indonesia,
Malaysia, USA and Vietnam, have been published yesterday (10 Feb
2006) in the Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the
United States of America (PNAS), as an online paper before print. See
"Establishment of multiple sublineages of H5N1 influenza virus in
Asia: Implications for pandemic control" by H. Chen, G. J. D. Smith,
K. S. Li et al. Abstract accessible at
<http://www.pnas.org/cgi/content/abstract/0511120103v1>).
The said abstract includes the following statement: "Our data show
that H5N1 influenza virus has continued to spread from its
established source in southern China to other regions through
transport of poultry and bird migration. The identification of
regionally distinct sublineages contributes to the understanding of
the mechanism for the perpetuation and spread of H5N1, providing
information that is directly relevant to control of the source of
infection in poultry. It points to the necessity of surveillance that
is geographically broader than previously supposed and that includes
H5N1 viruses of greater genetic and antigenic diversity."
The findings and the said statement confirm that, in addition to
migratory bird flyways as a plausible route for the spread of H5N1,
possible other routes are not to be overlooked. In this respect,
data on imports of poultry (short-distance poultry for slaughter,
long-distance breeding material) from infected countries, as well as
possible (illegal?) trade in captive birds, are to be taken into
consideration, prescribing the needed control activities. Wild birds
cannot be controlled nor eliminated; their contact with domestic
poultry, and human-regulated international movements of infected
animals/products, should be prevented and deserve appropriate
international support. - Mod.AS]
